-- Asia Fuel Oil Refining Margins Advance as Shipping Demand in China Climbs
-- B y   A n n   K o h
-- 2010-10-26T05:18:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-26/asian-fuel-oil-margins-rise-as-china-s-demand-for-fuel-for-shipping-rises.html
Refining margins for making fuel oil
rose amid speculation that China’s demand for commodities will
boost shipping fuel consumption. The crack spreads of gasoil and
naphtha declined.  Fuel Oil  Fuel oil ’s discount to Dubai, or the crack spread, narrowed
to $6.53 a barrel at 10:02 a.m. Singapore time from $6.69 a
barrel yesterday, according to data from PVM Oil Associates.  Ships that haul dry-bulk commodities such as iron ore, coal
and grains will remain in demand to carry cargoes to China,
according to Commodore Research. About 38 vessels were used to
transport iron ore last week, up 15 percent from the prior seven
days, New York-based Commodore said yesterday in an e-mailed
report.  Middle Distillates  Processing profits from making  gasoil  fell 6 cents to
$13.24 a barrel, PVM data showed.  Gasoil  swaps dropped 0.6
percent to $93.85 a barrel.  Jet-kerosene’s  premium  over gasoil, or the  regrade , lost 5
cents to $1.15 a barrel, PVM data showed. That’s up from 65
cents a month ago. The spread reached $1.40 on Oct. 19, the
highest since June 8.  U.S. supplies of distillate fuel, a category that includes
heating oil and diesel, probably declined for a fifth week as
distributors took deliveries before winter and fuel exports to
Europe increased, a Bloomberg News survey showed.  Naphtha  Naphtha for delivery to Japan declined relative to Brent
crude futures today. The premium fell to $139.04 a metric ton
from $139.65 at the end of trading in Asia yesterday, according
to Bloomberg calculations.  Open-specification naphtha cargoes delivered in the second
half of December were bid at $766.50 a metric ton against offers
at $769.50, according to data from Ginga Petroleum Singapore Pte.
First-half January lots were bid at $764 a ton compared with
offers at $767 a ton.  Naphtha  for delivery from mid-December to mid-January was
at $771.75 a ton yesterday, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  Mangalore Refinery & Petrochemicals Ltd. sold 35,000 tons
of naphtha to Royal Dutch Shell Plc in a tender that closed last
week, according to three traders who participate in the market.  Refinery Outages  TonenGeneral Sekiyu K.K., a subsidiary of Exxon Mobil Corp.,
resumed operations of the No. 2 and No. 3 crude distillation
units yesterday at its Wakayama refinery, according to Rim
Intelligence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
